MENINGITIS-NIGERIA (9) and USDA TO LOWER STANDARDS FOR POULTRY
==============================================================
Subject: the Herald Tribune wrote...
On Friday March 15 1996, the International Herald Tribune wrote on
page 2:
"Meningitis Spreads in Africa.
Geneva (AP) - An epidemic of meningitis is spreading western Africa, the
World Health Organization said Thursday. The death toll in Nigeria rose to
3,386, an increase of more than 700 in a week, the UN agency said. Almost
19,000 people have been infected. In Burkino Faso, 7,476 people have
contracted the disease and 668 have died. In Niger, 4,808 people are
infected, with 503 deaths so far. In Chad, 244 cases have been diagnosed,
with 19 dead."
On Friday March 15 1996, the International Herald Tribune wrote on
page 3:
"Sweeping changes in the inspection of meat and poultry are planned by the
Department of Agriculture, but the new rules will not include mandatory
testing by industry for the salmonella bacteria that kill more than 4,000
people a year and sicken many more. (NY Times)"
[Moderator: Charles H. Calisher <ccalisher@vines.colostate.edu> Arthropod-
borne and Infectious Diseases Laboratory, Colorado State University, Fort
Collins, CO 80523: TEL: (970) 491-8604; FAX (970) 491-8323]

